{{speciesbox | name = Chile Darwin's frog | image = | status = PE | status_system = IUCN3.1 | status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{cite journal | author = IUCN SSC Amphibian Specialist Group | title = ''Rhinoderma rufum'' | journal = [[IUCN Red List of Threatened Species]] | volume= 2015 | page = e.T19514A79809567 | publisher = [[IUCN]] | year = 2015 | url = https://dx.doi.org/10.2305/IUCN.UK.2015-4.RLTS.T19514A79809567.en | accessdate = 7 July 2017}}</ref> | taxon = Rhinoderma rufum | authority = ([[Rodolfo Amando Philippi|Philippi]], 1902) | synonyms = ''Heminectes rufus'' <small>Philippi, 1902</small> | synonyms_ref = <ref name=Frost/> | range_map = Mapa rhinoderma rufum.svg | range_map_upright = 0.5 | range_map_alt = Range of ''Rhinoderma rufum'' (in red) | range_map_caption = Range of ''Rhinoderma rufum'' (in red) }}
The '''Chile Darwin's frog''' (''Rhinoderma rufum''),<ref name=Frost/> also called the '''northern Darwin's frog''',<ref name=IUCN/><ref name="SearsSoto-Azat2013">{{cite journal |last1=Sears|first1=Michael|last2=Soto-Azat |first2=Claudio|last3=Valenzuela-Sánchez |first3=Andrés|last4=Clarke |first4=Barry T.|last5=Busse |first5=Klaus|last6=Ortiz |first6=Juan Carlos|last7=Barrientos|first7=Carlos|last8=Cunningham|first8=Andrew A. |title=Is chytridiomycosis driving Darwin’s frogs to extinction? |journal=PLoS ONE |volume=8 |issue=11 |year=2013 |pages=e79862 |issn=1932-6203 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0079862 |pmid=24278196 |pmc=3835940}}</ref> is one of only two members of the family [[Rhinodermatidae]].<ref name="Frost genus"/> It is [[Endemism|endemic]] to central [[Chile]], although it might well be extinct.<ref name=IUCN/>
==Description== The Chile Darwin's frog has a snout to vent length of about {{convert|32|mm|1|abbr=on}}. It has a fleshy proboscis, slender limbs and feet webbed between the first and second, and the second and third toes. The dorsal colour is variable but is usually some shade of brown or green, or a mixture of the two. The ventral surface is mottled in black and white.<ref name=AmphibiaWeb>{{cite web |url=http://amphibiaweb.org/cgi-bin/amphib_query?where-genus=Rhinoderma&where-species=rufum |title=''Rhinoderma rufum'' |author1=Whittaker, Kellie |author2=Chantasirisivisal, Peera |date=2008-09-08 |work=AmphibiaWeb |accessdate=2013-12-06}}</ref>
==Biology== The Chile Darwin's frog is diurnal and feeds on small insects and other invertebrates. The female lays a small clutch of eggs on moist ground. About a week later the embryos are beginning to move within the eggs and the male picks them up and stores them in his vocal sac. He keeps them there until they have developed a functioning gut and then transports them to a suitable water body and releases them. The tadpoles grow further in the water and undergo [[metamorphosis]] there. This development is in contrast to that of the Darwin's frog (''Rhinoderma darwinii'') tadpoles which complete their development in their parent's vocal sac.<ref name=AmphibiaWeb/>
==Distribution and habitat== The Chile Darwin's frog has a very restricted range in central Chile, being found in [[Talca Province]] and southwards to [[Bío Bío Province]], between from 33° 30'S to 37° 50'S. Very little is known about this species, but its natural habitats are probably [[temperate forest]]s, rivers and swamps. It has been found in wet beech forests at altitudes of between {{convert|50|and|500|m}} above sea level. The species was [[Sympatry|sympatric]] with [[Darwin's frog|Rhinoderma darwinii]] in the region surrounding [[Concepción, Chile|Concepcion]], near the southern extremities of Rhinoderma rufum's distribution.<ref name=IUCN/><ref name=AmphibiaWeb/><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Soto-Azat|first=Claudio|last2=Valenzuela-Sánchez|first2=Andrés|last3=Collen|first3=Ben|last4=Rowcliffe|first4=J. Marcus|last5=Veloso|first5=Alberto|last6=Cunningham|first6=Andrew A.|date=2013-06-12|title=The Population Decline and Extinction of Darwin’s Frogs|url=http://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0066957|journal=PLOS ONE|language=en|volume=8|issue=6|pages=e66957|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0066957|issn=1932-6203}}</ref>
==Conservation status== The Chile Darwin's frog is currently listed as "Critically Endangered" by the [[IUCN]], but as there have been no confirmed sightings since around 1981, it may already be [[extinct]]. The main threats it faces are destruction of the pine forests in which it lives and building work but its steep decline is unexplained. It may be the victim of disease such as [[chytridiomycosis]] but this had not been reported in Chile when the decline started.<ref name=IUCN/><ref>[https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2008/01/080124132336.htm EDGE Amphibians: World's Weirdest Creatures Just Got Weirder by Science daily]. Sciencedaily.com (January 25, 2008). Retrieved on 2013-01-02.</ref> If still [[Extant taxon|extant]], it is likely to be threatened by [[habitat loss]], [[pollution]], and infection from ''[[Batrachochytrium dendrobatidis]]''.<ref name="SearsSoto-Azat2013"/>
On January 21, 2008, Evolutionarily Distinct and Globally Endangered (EDGE), per chief Helen Meredith identified nature's most weird, wonderful and [[endangered]] [[species]]: "The EDGE [[amphibians]] are amongst the most remarkable and unusual species on the planet and yet an alarming 85% of the top 100 are receiving little or no conservation attention." The top 10 endangered species (in the [[List of endangered animal species]] include: the [[Chinese giant salamander]] (''Andrias davidianus''), a relative of the [[hellbender]] (''Cryptobranchus alleganiensus''); the tiny [[Gardiner's Seychelles frog]] (''Sooglossus gardineri''); the limbless [[Boulengerula niedeni|Sagalla caecilian]] (''Boulengerula niedeni''); the [[Table Mountain ghost frog]] (''Heleophryne rosei''); the Mexican [[lungless salamander]]s; the [[Scaphiophryne gottlebei|Malagasy rainbow frog]] (''Scaphiophryne gottlebei''); the Chile Darwin's frog (''Rhinoderma rufum''); and the [[Betic midwife toad]] (''Alytes dickhilleni'').<ref>Jeremy Lovell (January 20, 2008) [https://www.reuters.com/article/latestCrisis/idUSL2038808 Reuters, Giant newt, tiny frog identified as most at risk]. Reuters.com. Retrieved on 2013-01-02.</ref><ref>Ian Sample (January 21, 2008) [https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2008/jan/21/conservation guardian.co.uk, Drive to save weird and endangered amphibians]. Guardian. Retrieved on 2013-01-02.</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/environment/gallery/2008/jan/21/wildlife.conservation World's weirdest amphibians]. Guardian (January 21, 2008). Retrieved on 2013-01-02.</ref>
