{{Infobox scientist |name = |image = FOURNET.jpg |image_size = |caption = Jean-Baptiste Fournet |birth_date = {{birth date|1801|5|15|mf=y}} |birth_place = [[Strasbourg]] |death_date = {{death date and age|1869|1|8|1801|5|15|mf=y}} |death_place = [[Lyon]] |residence = |citizenship = |nationality = France |ethnicity = |field = [[geology]], [[metallurgy]] |work_institutions = [[University of Lyon]] |alma_mater = [[Mines ParisTech|École des Mines]] |doctoral_advisor = |doctoral_students = |known_for = |author_abbrev_bot = |author_abbrev_zoo = |influences = |influenced = |prizes = |religion = |footnotes = |signature = }} '''Joseph Jean Baptiste Xavier Fournet''' (May 15, 1801 &ndash; January 8, 1869), French [[geologist]] and [[Metallurgy|metallurgist]], was born at [[Strasbourg]].
He was educated at the ''[[École nationale supérieure des mines de Paris|École des Mines]]'' in [[Paris, France|Paris]], and after considerable experience as a mining engineer he was in 1834 appointed professor of [[geology]] at [[Lyon]].
He was a man of wide knowledge and extensive research, and wrote memoirs on chemical and mineralogical subjects, on eruptive rocks, on the structure of the [[Jura mountains|Jura]], the [[metamorphism]] of the Western [[Alps]], on the formation of [[Oolite|oolitic]] [[limestone]]s, on [[kaolin]]ization and on metalliferous veins. On [[metallurgy|metallurgical]] subjects he also was an acknowledged authority; and he published observations on the order of [[sulphur]]ability of metals (''loi de Fournet'').
He died in Lyon. His chief publications were: ''Études sur les dépôts métallifères'' (Paris, 1834); [https://books.google.com/books/about/Histoire_de_la_Dolomie.html?id=jPkTAAAAQAAJ ''Histoire de la dolomie''] (Lyon, 1847); ''De l'extension des terrains houillers'' (1855); and [https://books.google.com/books?id=Gv0TAAAAQAAJ ''Géologie lyonnaise''] (Lyon, 1861).
