{{italic title}} {{Infobox website | name = Quanta Magazine | logo = | logo_size = | logo_alt = | logo_caption = <!-- or: | logocaption = --> | screenshot = | collapsible = <!-- set as "on", "y", etc, otherwise omit/leave blank --> | collapsetext = <!-- collapsible area's heading (default "Screenshot"); omit/leave blank if collapsible not set --> | background = <!-- for collapsetext heading; default grey (gainsboro) --> | screenshot_size = | screenshot_alt = | caption = | url = {{URL|https://www.quantamagazine.org/}} | slogan = | areas = | offices = | traded to date = | commercial = No | type = Online magazine | registration = | language = English | num_users = | content_license = <!-- or: | content_licence = --> | programming_language = | owner = [[Simons Foundation]] | author = <!-- or: creator / authors / creators --> | editor = <!-- or: | editors = --> | launch_date = {{start date and age|2012|10|df=no}} | revenue = | alexa = <!-- {{IncreaseNegative}} {{steady}} {{DecreasePositive}} [http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/example.com ##] (US/Global MM/YYYY) --> | ip = | issn = <!-- ISSN, e.g. 1085-6706 (automatically linked to http://www.WorldCat.org) --> | oclc = <!-- OCLC number, useful where an ISSN has not been allocated (automatically linked to http://www.WorldCat.org) --> | current_status = | footnotes = }} '''''Quanta Magazine''''' is an editorially independent<ref>{{cite web |title=About Quanta Magazine |url=https://www.quantamagazine.org/about/ |work=Quanta Magazine |publisher=Simons Foundation}}</ref> [[online publication]] of the [[Simons Foundation]] covering developments in [[mathematics]], [[theoretical physics]], [[theoretical computer science]] and the basic [[life science]]s.
==Magazine== The articles in the magazine are freely available to read online.<ref>{{cite web |title=Quanta Magazine |url=https://www.lms.ac.uk/editorial/quanta-magazine |publisher=[[London Mathematical Society]] |accessdate=29 September 2016 |series=Press release}}</ref> Several publications like ''[[Scientific American]]'',<ref>{{cite news|title=Stories by Quanta Magazine|url=http://www.scientificamerican.com/author/quanta-magazine/|accessdate=5 October 2016|work=Scientific American}}</ref> [[Wired (magazine)|''Wired'']],<ref>{{cite news|title=Quanta Magazine|url=https://www.wired.com/tag/quanta-magazine/|accessdate=5 October 2016|work=Wired}}</ref> and ''[[The Atlantic]]'', as well as international science publications like ''[[Spektrum der Wissenschaft]]'',<ref>{{cite news|title=Quanta Magazine|url=http://www.spektrum.de/index/quanta-magazine-auf-deutsch/1436462|accessdate=1 February 2017|work=Spektrum der Wissenschaft}}</ref> have reprinted articles from ''Quanta Magazine''. ''Undark Magazine'' described ''Quanta Magazine'' as "highly regarded for its masterful coverage of complex topics in science and math."<ref>{{cite news|title=Hard-Sciences Magazine Goes to the Next Level|url=https://undark.org/2017/05/04/hard-sciences-magazine-goes-next-level/|accessdate=4 May 2017|work=Undark Magazine}}</ref> The science news aggregator ''RealClearScience'' ranked ''Quanta Magazine'' No. 2 on its list of "The Top 10 Websites for Science in 2016."<ref>{{cite news|title=The Top 10 Websites for Science in 2016 |url=http://www.realclearscience.com/blog/2016/11/14/the_top_10_websites_for_science_in_2016.html |publisher=RealClearScience |accessdate=14 November 2016}}</ref> Initially launched as ''Simons Science News''<ref>{{cite news|title=A Magazine or a Living Fossil? |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/05/07/science/a-glossy-science-magazine-or-living-fossil.html |publisher=The New York Times |accessdate=6 May 2013}}</ref> in October 2012, it was renamed to its current title in July 2013.<ref>{{cite web |author=Thomas Lin|title=Simons Science News Is Renamed Quanta Magazine |url=https://www.quantamagazine.org/20130716-simons-science-news-is-renamed-quanta-magazine/ |work=Quanta Magazine |publisher=Simons Foundation |accessdate=30 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=[[Carl Zimmer]]|title=My New Story for Scientific American & Quanta Magazine |url=http://phenomena.nationalgeographic.com/2013/07/17/how-things-get-complex-my-new-story-for-scientific-american-quanta-magazine/ |publisher=National Geographic |accessdate=17 July 2013}}</ref> ''Quanta'' was founded by the former [[New York Times]] journalist Thomas Lin, who is the magazine's first [[editor-in-chief]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Thomas Lin |url=https://www.quantamagazine.org/authors/thomas/ |work=Quanta Magazine |publisher=Simons Foundation |accessdate=30 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Reinventing The Boundaries of Science Journalism |url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/finding-the-next-einstein/201406/reinventing-the-boundaries-science-journalism |publisher=Psychology Today |accessdate=16 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Quanta Magazine’s Thomas Lin Spends His Days ‘Illuminating Science’ |url=http://observer.com/2016/05/quanta-magazines-thomas-lin/ |publisher=The Observer |accessdate=20 May 2016}}</ref> ''Quanta's'' two deputy editors are [[John Rennie (editor)]] and Michael Moyer, formerly of ''[[Scientific American]]''. Notable writers include [[K.C. Cole]], [[Dan Falk]], Kevin Hartnett, [[Erica Klarreich]], [[George Musser]], [[Jennifer Ouellette]], [[Frank Wilczek]], Natalie Wolchover and [[Carl Zimmer]]. On 2 May 2017 ''Quanta'' launched its redesigned and rebranded magazine website.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.quantamagazine.org/the-new-familiar-quanta/|title=The New Familiar Quanta {{!}} Quanta Magazine|last=Lin|first=Thomas|date=2017-05-02|work=Quanta Magazine|access-date=2017-05-06|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=}}</ref>
